The Israel Defense
Forces has actually

00:17:19.089 --> 00:17:21.730
copied off the
GeekCon model and they

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:23.844
have an event internal
for the intelligence corp

00:17:23.844 --> 00:17:25.760
and for Air Force that
they are doing in order

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:27.609
to build more creative things.

00:17:27.609 --> 00:17:30.540
And so we have done
that with Microsoft.

00:17:30.540 --> 00:17:32.690
So how can you do this?

00:17:32.690 --> 00:17:34.100
It's pretty easy.

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:35.860
It's a lot of work
but it's pretty easy.

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:39.780
So GeekCon, in order to
have it up and running,

00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:41.090
there was a spreadsheet.

00:17:41.090 --> 00:17:43.256
What a surprise, everything
is a spreadsheet, right?

00:17:43.256 --> 00:17:45.080
So first off, when
we started planning

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:47.840
for GeekCon X-- this is
this year-- we said, OK,

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:50.239
what do we want to do?

00:17:50.239 --> 00:17:51.780
What are the principles
that we have?

00:17:51.780 --> 00:17:54.750
We want bigger organizer
team, have it longer,

00:17:54.750 --> 00:17:57.710
do two pre-cons meaning
conferences that

00:17:57.710 --> 00:18:00.430
happened before in order
to help people team up

00:18:00.430 --> 00:18:01.680
and build bigger projects.

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:03.670
In order for them to
understand 3D printing,

00:18:03.670 --> 00:18:06.320
in order for them
to do Oculus Rift.

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:10.320
There's actually a project,
a submarine controlled Oculus

00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:11.790
Rift control
submarine this year.

00:18:11.790 --> 00:18:14.890
And many ways, that's because
of those pre-con structures.

00:18:14.890 --> 00:18:16.910
So these are the principles.

00:18:16.910 --> 00:18:18.240
This is what we wanted to do.

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:21.250
Bring in more women, get
internet to work finally,

00:18:21.250 --> 00:18:24.854
tenth year, we've never been
able to do good internet

00:18:24.854 --> 00:18:25.520
infrastructures.

00:18:25.520 --> 00:18:28.780
So these are the principles.

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:32.920
Then we went off and said,
OK, so these are the teams

00:18:32.920 --> 00:18:33.550
that we need.

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:37.290
There are 30 teams that are
charged with tear down, set

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:40.810
up, projects, website,
pretty much anything that

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:43.420
needs to happen in order
to get things going.

00:18:43.420 --> 00:18:45.530
And you then find owners
for each of those.

00:18:45.530 --> 00:18:48.120
These are the volunteers
that now there

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:50.880
are 30 of them instead of
the four that we are usually.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:53.310
And then the how to.

00:18:53.310 --> 00:18:55.091
The file is actually
called How To.

00:18:55.091 --> 00:18:56.340
And these are all the to do's.

00:18:56.340 --> 00:19:01.650
And surprisingly, the amount
of to do's is very, very deep

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:02.960
before the event.

00:19:02.960 --> 00:19:05.079
And then the event
itself runs itself.

00:19:05.079 --> 00:19:05.620
In many ways.

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:08.830
So 150 things that
need to happen.

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:10.870
All the must items,
if they don't happen,

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:12.630
there will be no GeekCon.

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:14.520
All the high items,
if they don't happen,

00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:16.380
it will be a OK GeekCon.

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:19.550
Medium, if you do the medium,
it will be an awesome GeekCon.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:21.170
And low, you never do.

00:19:21.170 --> 00:19:22.900
In startups, generally,
there is must,

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:25.140
muster and mustest
priority level.

00:19:25.140 --> 00:19:27.199
And the same with GeekCon.

00:19:27.199 --> 00:19:29.490
And this is what's going on
in the event itself, right?

00:19:29.490 --> 00:19:30.850
So very short.

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:35.850
If you look before it's about
70 items, but during the event

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:38.620
it's basically, OK, let's
get the teams going,

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:41.590
give them rooms, make sure
they have a refrigerator

00:19:41.590 --> 00:19:43.810
for the user generated
dinner, and the rest

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:45.590
will happen by itself.

00:19:45.590 --> 00:19:48.300
So the organizer team, most of
the stuff that we do is ahead.

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:51.797
Just making sure the best
projects will be selected,

00:19:51.797 --> 00:19:53.380
that there will be
the infrastructure,

00:19:53.380 --> 00:19:55.380
there will be a group
buy in case people

00:19:55.380 --> 00:19:57.190
need to buy many arduinos.

00:19:57.190 --> 00:20:01.040
But otherwise it's running
pretty much by itself.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:05.450
If you want to do a GeekCon
yourself, best way to do that

00:20:05.450 --> 00:20:08.390
is to experience
GeekCon by coming.

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:08.890
Right?

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:11.370
So 18th to 20th of September.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:13.250
This is what's
going on in Israel.

00:20:13.250 --> 00:20:16.300
We already have a lot of
pressure in doing it in the US.

00:20:16.300 --> 00:20:18.330
Philadelphia
volunteered to do it.

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:21.110
But basically anyone that
is interested in doing it,

00:20:21.110 --> 00:20:23.910
